<methodology slug="elicitation-techniques">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ba</group>
    <domain>business-analyst</domain>
    <summary>Structured techniques: interviews, observation, surveys, workshops, prototyping. Enforce triangulation (≥2 techniques per requirement) via synthesis artifacts with consent/PII markers.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>elicitation</tag>
      <tag>requirements</tag>
      <tag>stakeholder-engagement</tag>
      <tag>discovery</tag>
      <tag>triangulation</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>discovery</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Elicitation Techniques</title>

    <summary>Elicitation is the process of drawing out information from stakeholders about their needs, wants, and constraints — not just asking questions but using structured techniques to uncover stated and unstated requirements. Core techniques are: interviews (depth), workshops (consensus), observation (actual behavior), document analysis (existing state), surveys (breadth), prototyping (validation), focus groups (user perspective), and brainstorming (ideation). Each session produces a typed artifact committed to version control with consent and PII-redaction markers; a synthesis step extracts REQ stubs that cite at least two distinct technique sessions per requirement, enforcing triangulation as an empirical requirement quality gate.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Stakeholders cannot reliably articulate what they need in the abstract. Interviews surface stated needs; observation surfaces actual behavior — the gap between them is where the most valuable requirements live. Single-technique programs miss requirements; triangulation across at least two techniques per area is the empirical fix. Without a documented elicitation record, requirements lack the source attribution needed for impact analysis, regulated-industry audits, and conflict resolution.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Kickoff of a new initiative where stakeholder needs are vague, contradictory, or undocumented.</item>
        <item>Migration or replatforming projects where knowledge lives in a few senior employees' heads.</item>
        <item>Regulated domains (medical, fintech, gov) where elicitation evidence is part of the audit trail.</item>
        <item>Discovery sprints where the BA must triangulate a process within one week using mixed techniques.</item>
        <item>Distributed or async teams where surveys, recorded interviews, and async observation are the only feasible channels.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Solo founder or 2-person team where direct conversation is faster than scheduling formal sessions.</item>
        <item>Backlog refinement on a stable product — DoR conversations and slice discussions cover it.</item>
        <item>The answer is already in a spec, ADR, or RFC — read first, elicit only the gaps.</item>
        <item>Bug triage or incident postmortems — those have their own templates (5-whys, blameless retro).</item>
        <item>Stakeholders are unwilling or unavailable — surveys to non-responsive groups produce noise; escalate sponsorship instead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="interviews">
      <p>Purpose: gather detailed information from individuals. Best for deep understanding, sensitive topics, or stakeholders with unique knowledge.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Prepare a written interview guide with objectives, question types (open, closed, probing, clarifying), and pre-read materials. Send the guide 24 hours ahead.</statement>
        <rationale>Pre-reading produces 30-50% deeper sessions; unprepared stakeholders give surface-level answers that require follow-up interviews.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Open questions — explore: "Tell me about your process."</item>
        <item>Closed questions — confirm: "Do you use this daily?"</item>
        <item>Probing questions — dig deeper: "Why is that important?"</item>
        <item>Clarifying questions — ensure understanding: "So you mean...?"</item>
      </list>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cap interviews at 60 minutes. Past that, signal-to-noise collapses.</statement>
        <rationale>Fatigue produces unreliable notes and stakeholders disengage from the process.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="workshops">
      <p>Purpose: bring stakeholders together to build consensus on complex topics. Best when multiple perspectives are required.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use anonymous dot-voting or similar mechanisms to prevent the loudest voice from dominating. Record per-vote tallies, not names.</statement>
        <rationale>Workshop dynamics get hijacked without structured participation controls; consensus produced by loudest voice is not consensus.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cap workshops at 90 minutes with a hard break.</statement>
        <rationale>Past 90 minutes, participant attention degrades and minutes become unreliable.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="observation">
      <p>Purpose: see how work is actually done, not how it is described. Captures what interviews miss.</p>

      <list>
        <item>Passive — watch without interaction; produces unbiased view of the current state.</item>
        <item>Active — ask questions while observing; captures the rationale behind each step.</item>
        <item>Participant — join in the work; produces the deepest understanding.</item>
      </list>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pair observation with at least one other technique (interview or document analysis) for every requirement area.</statement>
        <rationale>Stated needs (interviews) differ from actual behavior (observation); skipping observation produces requirements that pass review and fail in production.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="document-analysis">
      <p>Purpose: extract requirements from existing materials — system documentation, process manuals, business rules, reports, regulations, previous project documents.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Treat every document-analysis claim as "as-documented" and cross-check against at least one observation or interview before promoting to a requirement.</statement>
        <rationale>Documentation typically lags actual implementation by 6-18 months; as-documented state is not as-implemented state.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="surveys-and-questionnaires">
      <p>Purpose: gather quantitative or broad input from large or geographically distributed stakeholder groups.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Surveys with less than 30% response rate are not data — they are anecdotes. Flag response rate in the synthesis report.</statement>
        <rationale>Low-response-rate surveys mislead with statistical framing; the real finding is that the stakeholder group did not engage.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Design with a target N and confidence interval before distributing. Pre-register the analysis plan to prevent post-hoc fishing.</statement>
        <rationale>Open-ended analysis produces artifacts that confirm pre-existing beliefs rather than surface new requirements.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="prototyping">
      <p>Purpose: validate understanding through tangible examples. Use only after divergent elicitation.</p>

      <list>
        <item>Paper — low fidelity, quick concept validation.</item>
        <item>Wireframe — low-medium fidelity, layout and flow.</item>
        <item>Mockup — medium-high fidelity, visual design.</item>
        <item>Working prototype — high fidelity, functional validation.</item>
      </list>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Never use prototyping as the first elicitation technique. Use only after interviews and/or observation have produced candidate requirements.</statement>
        <rationale>Prototyping anchors stakeholders on the prototype's affordances; they stop imagining alternatives and stop surfacing underlying needs.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="focus-groups">
      <p>Purpose: gather user perspectives on a topic from a group with similar characteristics. Best for validating assumptions about user segments.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="brainstorming">
      <p>Purpose: generate ideas rapidly in a group setting. Best at the start of a discovery phase.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="technique-selection-guide">
      <p>Match the information need to the technique(s) that will produce triangulated evidence.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every requirement must cite at least two distinct session IDs of different techniques before promotion from candidate to draft.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-source requirements lack triangulation; contradictions between sources are where the real requirements live.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Understand current process → Observation + Interview.</item>
        <item>Gather broad input → Survey + Focus group.</item>
        <item>Build consensus → Workshop.</item>
        <item>Validate design → Prototyping.</item>
        <item>Understand documentation → Document analysis.</item>
        <item>Generate ideas → Brainstorming workshop.</item>
        <item>Deep dive with expert → Interview.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Treat elicitation as a pipeline of evidence: each session produces a typed artifact committed to git under `.aidocs/elicitation/&lt;session-id&gt;/` with YAML frontmatter. A planner subagent reads `stakeholder-analysis/` and `ba-planning/` to schedule sessions and pick techniques; a transcriber agent ingests recordings and emits redacted transcripts; a synthesis agent extracts candidate requirements feeding `requirements-lifecycle/`. Triangulation is enforced by a check that every `REQ-NNN` cites ≥2 distinct `session_id`s of different techniques before promotion to draft. Humans run the live sessions; agents prepare guides, transcribe, synthesise, and flag contradictions — never speak to stakeholders unattended.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Capture consent in the frontmatter (`consent: true`, `consent_basis: email|signed|verbal+recorded`). No consent → no commit.</statement>
        <rationale>Stakeholder consent is a legal and ethical requirement; missing consent invalidates the entire session artifact.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Redact PII at ingest, not later — Presidio / spaCy NER pass before the transcript hits git. Keep raw recordings outside the repo (S3 with lifecycle policy).</statement>
        <rationale>PII in git is impossible to expunge; redact at the source, not in a post-hoc pass.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Distinguish *stated*, *observed*, and *inferred* needs in the synthesis output. Tag each REQ with its source tier; observed > stated > inferred for credibility.</statement>
        <rationale>The source of a requirement affects its credibility; inferred requirements without observation backing should be flagged for stakeholder validation.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cross-link every elicitation artifact to a `stakeholder-analysis/` ID and a `ba-planning/` deliverable; otherwise the corpus becomes unsearchable within a sprint.</statement>
        <rationale>Artifacts scattered across the project without cross-references become orphaned; linkage keeps them connected to the broader requirements lifecycle.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Keep an "open questions" log per session that the next session is expected to close. Track close-rate as a process metric.</statement>
        <rationale>Unclosed questions are the leading cause of incomplete requirements; tracking them as a metric highlights discovery thoroughness.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Recording retention policy lives next to the artifact (`retention: 365d`); a cron job purges past-due recordings and logs the deletion. GDPR-friendly by default.</statement>
        <rationale>Raw recordings contain sensitive information; automatic expiry is simpler than manual deletion and proves compliance.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run a "what did we miss" round at the end of every session — single highest-yield question, almost always uncovers an unspoken constraint.</statement>
        <rationale>This one question consistently surfaces requirements that all other techniques missed; it is the most cost-effective discovery technique per minute spent.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="common-failure-modes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Stated needs ≠ actual needs. Interviews capture what people say they do; observation captures what they actually do. Skipping observation produces requirements that pass review and fail in production.</description>
        <reason>Pair interviews with observation to close the stated-vs-actual gap. Single-technique programs will miss this.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Workshop dynamics get hijacked by the loudest voice. Without dot-voting or anonymous input the loudest stakeholder's view is recorded as "consensus".</description>
        <reason>Use anonymous voting mechanisms (Miro / FigJam / physical dots) to distribute voice equitably. Record per-vote tallies, not attributions.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Surveys with less than 30% response rate are not data, they are anecdotes with statistics applied — the README does not flag this.</description>
        <reason>Flag response rate in the synthesis report. If &lt; 30%, call it "anecdotal feedback" not "survey results."</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Document analysis surfaces the *as-documented* state, which is usually 6-18 months behind the *as-implemented* state. Pair with observation or it lies.</description>
        <reason>Always cross-check document claims against at least one observation or interview. Documentation is a starting point, not the source of truth.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Prototyping anchors stakeholders on the prototype's affordances; they stop imagining alternatives. Use only after divergent elicitation.</description>
        <reason>Prototyping is a validation technique, not an ideation technique. Run interviews/observation first; use prototypes to test, not explore.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Recordings + transcripts contain PII, salaries, performance complaints, customer names. Without a retention policy the elicitation archive becomes a compliance liability.</description>
        <reason>Redact PII at ingest (Presidio / spaCy). Keep raw recordings outside git with a lifecycle expiry (365 days). Comply by default.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Single-technique programs miss requirements. Triangulation (≥2 techniques per area) is the empirical fix; the README mentions it but does not enforce it.</description>
        <reason>Block requirement promotion to draft until ≥2 session_ids of different techniques are cited. Make triangulation a gate, not a suggestion.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>LLM-driven "interviews via chatbot" suppress emotional / non-verbal signal — sarcasm, hesitation, eye-rolls — which often carry the real requirement.</description>
        <reason>Humans run live sessions. Agents prepare guides, transcribe, synthesise. Never delegate the human conversation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Hallucinated stakeholders: synthesis agents invent plausible quotes ("the CFO said...") when none exists. Forbid any REQ without a `session_id + line_range` citation; reject outputs that fail the regex check.</description>
        <reason>Validate every REQ citation against the actual transcript before persisting. Spot-check 10% manually.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Leading-question generation: prep agents bias toward confirmation ("How much do you love feature X?"). Lint the guide for "don't you", "wouldn't", "isn't it true", and superlatives in question stems before sending.</description>
        <reason>Run a heuristic linter on the generated guide. Flag leading phrasing; human approves before distribution.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Transcription drift: Whisper hallucinates fluent text on silence / cross-talk. Always keep timestamps and require the synthesizer to cite line ranges; spot-check 10% manually.</description>
        <reason>Never trust STT output as-is. Require line-range citations; spot-check against audio. Preserve timestamps for correlation.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>PII echo: agents quote redacted spans back in summaries because the redaction was only on the transcript copy, not on the indexed embeddings. Redact at the embedding source, not just at view time.</description>
        <reason>Redact before any LLM ingests the text. Hash or replace sensitive fields in the raw transcript, not just in the summary view.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Sentiment flattening: LLM summaries strip frustration, sarcasm, hesitation. Preserve emotional markers in the transcript (`[long pause]`, `[laughs]`) and require the synthesizer to surface them as a separate "tone" field.</description>
        <reason>Preserve [long pause] and similar markers in the transcript. Require the agent to emit a "tone" field separately; humans review for missed signals.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Workshop minute generation tends toward consensus narrative. Force the agent to also emit a `dissents` list with named (or pseudonymised) speakers.</description>
        <reason>Generate minutes with explicit `dissents` section. Name speakers (or use pseudonyms for anonymity) for accountability.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Survey design agents balance question types but ignore Likert-scale calibration (5-point vs. 7-point, label asymmetry). Cap the agent to a known-good template; humans approve the final scale.</description>
        <reason>Never let agents invent the Likert scale. Use a pre-approved template with consistent labeling.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Document-analysis agents over-trust outdated docs. Require every "as-is" claim from a document to be cross-checked against ≥1 observation or interview.</description>
        <reason>Tag document-derived claims as "as-documented" and require cross-check before promotion to requirement.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Prototyping prompts: agents propose hi-fi prototypes too early because the corpus is full of them. Constrain to paper / wireframe at the divergent stage; promote fidelity only after stakeholder validation.</description>
        <reason>Constrain the prompt: "at this stage, only paper or wireframe fidelity." Enforce fidelity gatekeeping in the orchestration layer.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Token budget: long workshops produce 10-20k-token transcripts. Chunk per agenda item with overlap, not arbitrary windows; otherwise the synthesizer loses speaker context across chunks.</description>
        <reason>Chunk by agenda item, not by token count. Preserve overlap between chunks for context continuity.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Multi-language sessions: BA in Ukrainian, stakeholder in English mid-session — STT systems silently drop the minority language. Configure language hints per speaker; verify turn-by-turn.</description>
        <reason>Configure STT with language hints per speaker. Spot-check output for silently-dropped languages.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Triangulate every requirement: ≥2 techniques (e.g. interview + observation, or survey + workshop) before promoting from candidate to draft.</item>
        <item>Capture consent in the frontmatter. No consent → no commit.</item>
        <item>Redact PII at ingest, not later. Keep raw recordings outside the repo.</item>
        <item>Distinguish *stated*, *observed*, and *inferred* needs; tag each REQ with its source tier.</item>
        <item>Pre-read for interviews: send the guide 24h ahead. Stakeholders prepare, sessions get 30-50% deeper.</item>
        <item>Use anonymous dot-voting in workshops to neutralise the loudest-voice effect.</item>
        <item>Cap an interview at 60 minutes and a workshop at 90 with a hard break.</item>
        <item>Cross-link every elicitation artifact to a `stakeholder-analysis/` ID and a `ba-planning/` deliverable.</item>
        <item>Keep an "open questions" log per session that the next session is expected to close.</item>
        <item>Recording retention policy lives next to the artifact; a cron job purges past-due recordings.</item>
        <item>For surveys, design with a target N and confidence interval, not "send to everyone".</item>
        <item>Run a "what did we miss" round at the end of every session.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/interview-guide.md" purpose="Interview guide with objectives, background questions, main questions, closing questions, and action items."/>
      <template path="templates/workshop-agenda.md" purpose="Workshop agenda with time slots, activities, owners, materials, and expected outputs."/>
      <template path="templates/session-check.py" purpose="Pre-commit validator for elicitation session artifacts: checks frontmatter, consent, PII-redaction status."/>
    </templates>

